First, you'll need to make sure that your tablet has a camera. Most tablets have a rear-facing camera, but some may have a front-facing camera as well. Once you've confirmed that your tablet has a camera, you can use the ObjectRecognition API to recognize objects in the images captured by the camera.

To use the ObjectRecognition API, you'll need to create an instance of the `ObjectRecognition` class and pass in the camera preview as a `SurfaceTexture` object. You can then use the `recognizeObject` method to recognize objects in the preview frame.

Here's an example of how you might use the ObjectRecognition API to recognize objects in a camera preview:
```
// Create a new instance of the ObjectRecognition class
ObjectRecognition recognition = new ObjectRecognition();

// Get a reference to the camera preview
SurfaceTexture preview = ...;

// Create a new texture for the preview frame
Texture texture = new Texture(preview.getWidth(), preview.getHeight());

// Draw the preview frame onto the texture
GLES20.glBindTexture(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_2D, texture.getId());
GLES20.glTexParameterf(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_2D, GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_MIN_FILTER, GLES20.GL_NEAREST);
GLES20.glTexParameterf(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_2D, GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_MAG_FILTER, GLES20.GL_NEAREST);
GLES20.glTexImage2D(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_2D, 0, GLES20.GL_RGBA_8888, preview.getWidth(), preview.getHeight(), 0, GLES20.GL_RGBA, GLES20.GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE, null);

// Recognize objects in the preview frame
recognition.recognizeObject(texture, new ObjectRecognition.ObjectRecognitionListener() {
